      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What to Expect When Selling in Holland Park West
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Holland Park West offers buyers a quieter residential alternative to Holland Park with similar school access and city proximity. Sellers benefit from a practical, family-focused buyer pool.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Holland Park West sits to the south and west of Holland Park, sharing its school catchments and city access while maintaining a slightly more suburban character. The suburb is predominantly post-war residential, with a mix of original brick and timber homes and a growing number that have been substantially renovated or rebuilt. It attracts buyers who value the same inner-south amenity as Holland Park but who may be finding Holland Park itself priced above their range, making Holland Park West a natural alternative.</p>

      <p>The suburb's price trajectory has followed Holland Park's improvement, and sellers who purchased five or more years ago have generally seen meaningful capital growth. The opportunity now is to position correctly for the next wave of buyers moving along this corridor from the inner south toward more affordable alternatives to Coorparoo and Greenslopes. A well-presented Holland Park West home that is priced with reference to Holland Park comparables, not just internal comparables, will generate interest from a broader buyer pool.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Holland Park West</h2>
      <p>Families are the primary buyer, and many are coming directly from the Holland Park market having been unable to find the right property at the right price. First home buyers and upsizing couples are also active at the lower end of the suburb's range. The buyer profile is practical and value-oriented: these are buyers who have done their research, know what comparable homes are selling for across the corridor, and want a fair deal on a home they can live in without immediate major expenditure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Holland Park West</h2>
      <p>Land size and the quality of outdoor space are the primary value drivers. A home with a generous backyard, north-facing orientation and a functional outdoor entertaining area will consistently outperform a smaller or poorly oriented property in the same street. Proximity to the schools is a meaningful factor, and homes within easy walking distance of catchment schools attract a premium from the family buyer segment. The condition of the kitchen and bathrooms is the internal factor that most reliably appears in buyer feedback as either a positive or a reason for hesitation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for sale</h2>
      <p>Holland Park West buyers inspect carefully and negotiate on condition. Pre-sale preparation should address any deferred maintenance first, then focus on presentation. Fresh paint, clean flooring and a tidy garden are the baseline. For homes with dated kitchens or bathrooms, even modest updates, new handles, updated tapware, fresh tile grout, can shift buyer perception significantly without requiring a full renovation. The goal is to present a home that looks after itself, where the buyer's first thought at inspection is whether they like it rather than how much work it needs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Campaign approach</h2>
      <p>Holland Park West typically suits private treaty with a clearly positioned price. The buyer pool is practically oriented and tends to engage more readily when a price is clear. Auction can work for homes at the upper end of the suburb's range or those with development potential, but it requires a well-prepared buyer pool and clear comparable sales to anchor expectations. The most important variable in any campaign for a Holland Park West property is the accuracy of the initial price: buyers here have access to comparable data across Holland Park and Holland Park West and will respond quickly to a correctly priced listing, and disengage just as quickly from an overpriced one.</p>


      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Holland Park West</h2>
      <p>Holland Park West's selling market closely follows its neighbour Holland Park, with spring (September to November) as the primary window. The suburb sits south of Holland Park and borders Tarragindi, occupying a price band that attracts buyers who need to be slightly more budget-conscious than those targeting Holland Park proper. Family buyers are the dominant buyer group, and they time moves to the school calendar: enrolment deadline purchases concentrate between July and October. Holland Park West benefits from the same inner-south access story as Holland Park, and buyers active in both suburbs arrive at Holland Park West when Holland Park prices feel stretched. That spillover is most pronounced in spring when inner-south buyers have been competing actively for several months.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Holland Park West</h2>
      <p>Holland Park West homes typically sell in 28 to 40 days. The buyer pool is solid but somewhat narrower than Holland Park, partly because the suburb has less of a defined identity beyond its neighbour's brand and partly because its northern sections shade into Tarragindi territory at the lower price points. Homes on the streets that are genuinely closer to Holland Park's character precinct move faster than those that are effectively deep in Tarragindi. The suburb is primarily owner-occupier territory, which means committed buyers who are not going to chip on price once committed. Well-presented family homes with good school-zone positioning sell at the faster end of the range consistently across both peak seasons.</p>

